The ''Kojiki'' similarly mentions Takenukawawake's involvement during Emperor Sujin's reign but describes his expedition differently. According to this account, he and Ōhiko no Mikoto met in a place called "Aitsu" (modern-day {{ill|Aizu|ja|会津|12=draft}} in {{ill|Fukushima Prefecture|ja|福島県|12=draft}}), which was named in reference to their encounter. This tale is part of a series of {{ill|place-name origin stories|ja|地名起源説話|12=draft}}.

== Descendants ==
Takenukawawake is recognized as the ancestor of the Abe clan. The ''{{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku|12=draft}}'' specifically lists the following clans as his descendants:
* '''Takeda no Atai''' (竹田臣) – Recognized as a descendant of Takenukawawake through Ōhiko no Mikoto.{{Sfn|武渟川別（古代氏族）|2010th year }}

Additionally, the ''{{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|12=draft}}'' states that the {{ill|Nasu clan|ja|那須氏|12=draft}}, rulers of the northeastern part of {{ill|Tochigi Prefecture|ja|栃木県|12=draft}}, trace their origins to Takenukawawake.{{Sfn|国史大辞典}}

== Historical Evaluation ==
Takenukawawake's mission to the "Eastern Twelve Regions" may reflect later administrative structures rather than historical reality. The historicity of the Four Commanders of the Four Roads remains a topic of debate.{{Sfn|宝賀|2013rd year |p=38-59}}

