The ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}'' refers to him as "Takenukawawake" or "Takenukawabake," while the ''{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojiki|qq=}}'' uses the name "Takenunakawawake no Mikoto" (建沼河別命). He is known as a son of {{ill|Ōhiko-no-Mikoto|ja|大彦命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōhiko-no-Mikoto|qq=}}, a prince of {{ill|Emperor Kōgen|ja|孝元天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Kōgen|qq=}}, and is regarded as the ancestor of the {{ill|Abe clan|ja|阿倍氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Abe clan|qq=}}.

Takenukawawake was one of the {{ill|Four Commanders of the Four Roads|ja|四道将軍|1=Shidō Shōgun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Four Commanders of the Four Roads|13=User:Immanuelle/Shidō Shōgun|qq=}}, who were dispatched to pacify different regions of Japan. He was sent to the {{ill|Tōkaidō region|ja|東海道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tōkaidō region|qq=}}. During the reign of {{ill|Emperor Suinin|ja|垂仁天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Suinin|qq=}}, he was recognized as one of the five ''maetsukimi'' (大夫), or "chief retainers."

== Historical Records ==

=== Genealogy ===
