The ''Nihon Shoki'' states that Takenukawawake was sent to the Tōkaidō region on September 9 of the 10th year of Emperor Sujin's reign. He is mentioned alongside {{ill|Ōhiko-no-Mikoto|ja|大彦命|1=Ōhiko-no-Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōhiko-no-Mikoto|qq=}} (dispatched to the Hokuriku region), [[:en:Kibitsuhiko-no-mikoto|Kibitsuhiko no Mikoto]] (sent to the Sanyō region), and {{ill|Tanba-no-Michinushi-no-Mikoto|lt=Tanba-no-Michinushi-no-Mikoto|lt=Tanba Michinushi no Mikoto|ja|丹波道主命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tanba Michinushi no Mikoto|qq=}} (sent to Tanba Province). These four commanders were collectively called the {{ill|Four Commanders of the Four Roads|ja|四道将軍|1=Shidō Shōgun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Four Commanders of the Four Roads|13=User:Immanuelle/Shidō Shōgun|qq=}}.{{Sfn|武渟川別（古代氏族）|2010th year }}

Takenukawawake and his fellow commanders began their expeditions on October 22 and successfully reported the pacification of their assigned regions on April 28 of the following year.

In the 60th year of Emperor Sujin's reign, Takenukawawake and [[:en:Kibitsuhiko-no-mikoto|Kibitsuhiko no Mikoto]] were ordered to execute {{ill|Izumo Furune|ja|出雲振根|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izumo Furune|qq=}} for treason. During the reign of Emperor Suinin, he was one of five ''maetsukimi'' tasked with overseeing religious rituals and ensuring harmony between the imperial court and the deities.{{Sfn|武渟川別（古代氏族）|2010th year }}

=== ''Kojiki'' Account ===
The ''Kojiki'' similarly mentions Takenukawawake's involvement during Emperor Sujin's reign but describes his expedition differently. According to this account, he and Ōhiko-no-Mikoto met in a place called "Aitsu" (modern-day [[:en:Aizu|Aizu]] in [[:en:Fukushima Prefecture|Fukushima Prefecture]]), which was named in reference to their encounter. This tale is part of a series of {{ill|place-name origin stories|ja|地名起源説話|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/place-name origin stories|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}.

== Descendants ==
Takenukawawake is recognized as the ancestor of the Abe clan. The ''[[:en:Shinsen Shōjiroku|Shinsen Shōjiroku]]'' specifically lists the following clans as his descendants:
* '''Takeda no Atai''' (竹田臣) – Recognized as a descendant of Takenukawawake through Ōhiko-no-Mikoto.{{Sfn|武渟川別（古代氏族）|2010th year }}

Additionally, the ''[[:en:Kujiki|Sendai Kuji Hongi]]'' states that the {{ill|Nasu clan|ja|那須氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nasu clan|qq=}}, rulers of the northeastern part of [[:en:Tochigi Prefecture|Tochigi Prefecture]], trace their origins to Takenukawawake.{{Sfn|国史大辞典}}

== Historical Evaluation ==
Takenukawawake's mission to the "Eastern Twelve Regions" may reflect later administrative structures rather than historical reality. The historicity of the Four Commanders of the Four Roads remains a topic of debate.{{Sfn|宝賀|2013rd year |p=38-59}}

